  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Preface to Monk Gyeong's Journey to Jirisan Mountain
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the Western lands, no sage surpasses Buddha himself. In the Eastern realm, no mountain rises higher than Jirisan. Those who follow the Buddha's teaching take him as their standard, yet even Nagarjuna, Asvaghosa, Bodhidharma, and Linji pale beneath his radiance. Why should it be different for those who seek the sacred mountains of our Eastern lands? Geumgangsan stands majestic in the east, Myohyangsan in the north, Guweolsan in the west—yet when one ascends Jirisan to the south, these three great peaks shrink beneath one's gaze like mere mounds of earth. And that is not all! The great mountains of the world—Hengshan, Taishan, Songshan, and Huashan—must themselves retreat in shame.

    Monk Gyeong is a true seeker of the Buddha's way. In his youth, he served under Lord Deokyeon with such humility that no task was beneath him. In his later years, embracing the Buddhist path, he cast aside worldly trappings, wandered through the sacred mountains, and his precepts shone with crystalline purity. Those devoted to the Way competed to follow him. Eventually, journeying from Daebang, he came to Jirisan, ascended Banyabong, traversed Cheonwangbong, offered prayers at the high temple, and sought immortals in the Blue Crane Grotto. Now, gathering his robes and staff, he dwells in Bongcheonsa, burning incense as he sits facing the wall, seeking to perceive what his teacher calls the true nature of being. Gyeong's purpose transcends mere personal salvation—he labors to plant seeds of merit for his former lord, to ferry him across the waters of karma toward future blessedness. Is this not the very essence of loyalty?

    I am a follower of Confucius, yet in my love of mountains, I am no different from Gyeong. The three great peaks remain in distant lands, beyond my reach, yet they dwell constantly in my heart. When in the Year of the Rabbit I served as magistrate of Hamyang, with Jirisan lying in my southern domain, I finally ascended its summit with kindred spirits, setting aside my administrative duties. I tasted something of what the Master meant when he spoke of making the world seem small. Five years have passed since then, yet in my dreams, my spirit never leaves Cheonwangbong. How I wish to climb it again with someone like Gyeong, to gaze freely upon the mountains rising and falling, the transformations of great creatures, the movements of sun and moon—and thereby clear the melancholy that clouds my mind.

    Yet here is the difference: Gyeong beholds movement as movement and stillness as stillness in their pure forms. I, however, seek stillness through movement and movement through stillness. But movement and stillness are not truly separate—this difference between us is not by design. Such is the teaching of both our masters, and truthfully, I do not fully comprehend why.
  footnotes:
    - Buddha (Muni/Mouni) is contrasted with the great Buddhist philosophers and patriarchs who followed, establishing the hierarchical structure of Buddhist tradition.
    - The three mountains (Geumgangsan, Myohyangsan, Guweolsan) represent the sacred geography of Korea, each associated with distinct spiritual qualities.
    - Banyabong and Cheonwangbong are peaks within Jirisan, the highest mountain in southwestern Korea, making this both a physical and spiritual journey.
    - The author uses Confucian and Daoist philosophy to interpret the Buddhist monk's journey, suggesting a synthesis of Korean intellectual traditions.
    - The final meditation on movement and stillness reflects both Buddhist and Neo-Confucian philosophical concerns about the nature of being and perception.
